{"cursor":"6920","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, there are many senses in which a sequence or a series is said to\nbe convergent. This article describes various modes (senses or species) of\nconvergence in the settings where they are defined. For a list of 'modes of\nconvergence', see Modes of convergence (annotated index)\n\nNote that each of the following objects is a special case of the types preceding\nit: sets, topological spaces, uniform spaces, TAGs (topological abelian groups),\nnormed spaces, Euclidean spaces, and the real/complex numbers. Also, note that\nany metric space is a uniform space.\n","linknr":133,"url":"Modes_of_convergence","recorded":1362552157,"links":10,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","annotated_index","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Topology","Convergence (mathematics)"],"headings":["Elements of a topological space","Series of elements in a topological abelian group","Convergence of sequence of functions on a topological space","Series of functions on a topological abelian group","Functions defined on a measure space","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/7/5/4753c096c57ef4ca707395d16bc3b6ca.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/d/c/2dca2b6fa565bef3e7c831bc19e009cc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/b/4/ab458700997e8b2f7b858a93a1e02c2f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/b/4/ab458700997e8b2f7b858a93a1e02c2f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/b/4/ab458700997e8b2f7b858a93a1e02c2f.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["modes_of_convergence","annotated_index"],["set","mathematics"],["net","mathematics"],["filter","mathematics"],["series","mathematics"],["domain","mathematics"],["modes_of_convergence","annotated_index"],["net","mathematics"],["filter","mathem